                 --Hungarian Notation--

Hungarian Variable Naming Notation:

Hungarian notation basically encodes the variable type and scope of the
variable in the name of the variable itself.

There are 4 parts to it:
1) The variable's scope
2) Is it an array?
3) The variable's type
4) The variable's name

The variable's scope
--------------------
At the basic level, there are two types of scope.

- Local scope
- Module-level scope

If a variable has been declared inside of a function, then its scope is
local.  Otherwise, the variable can be used anywhere in the file, and
it has module-level scope.

If the variable has module-level scope, then start your variable name with
an "m".  If it has local scope, then do not add anything to the variable
name.


Is it an array?
---------------
In LPC, arrays are designated by use of the "*" when declaring variables.

For example:
  int  iIndex;    // This is not an array.
  int *aiSize;    // This is an array of integers.

If your variable is an array, then you add an "a" to the variable name.  The
"a" goes after the "m" mentioned above if your variable has module-level
scope.  If your variable is not an array, then do not add anything to the
variable name.

The variable's type
-------------------
Basically, this is taking the variable type (IE, int, string, mixed, etc.)
and shortening it to 1 unique letter so that you know what the variable's
type is every time you look at it.

The LPC Unique letter for each variable type is:
i  : integer
ib : integer used as a bitfield
m  : mapping
o  : object
s  : string
t  : status
x  : mixed

Whatever type your variable is, add the unique letter to the variable name.
The variable type letter goes after the "m" and the "a" if they exist.  It
is not allowable to not encode the variable type into the name.

The variable's name
-------------------

This is the easy part.  It is what you call your variable.  The variable
name should be descriptive of the function of the variable, and should use
proper case.

All that "proper case" means is that you should capitalize the first letter
of the variable name as well as all letters of "new words" inside the
variable name, and that you should not use underscores to separate the "new
words."

Examples
--------

  iCount: local integer variable
 aiCount: local array of integers
maiCount: module level array of integers

 mIDsToNames: local mapping
mmIDsToNames: module level mapping

asNames: local array of strings

int iCount;
int *aiCount;
string *asNames;
object oPerson;

The second part: WHY should I use Hungarian notation?
-----------------------------------------------------
At its simplest, because redundancy in variable naming is a good thing.

If you have a long file which contains a global variable named something
generic without the scope and type encoded in the name, then by the time
you reach the end of the file and spot a line which uses that variable,
you may have forgotten what kind of variable it is.  If, however, your
variable uses Hungarian notation, you can look at the variable name and
you will immediately know that it is, for example, a module-level array
of mappings which you're using to store Responses (IE, mamResponses).

